source.dataPublisherSource: IMF Direction of Trade Statistics data set, manuscripts
source.additionalInfo:
To calculate country imports from the rest of the world, the total value of imports by country, per year, is divided by the country's GDP. 

The time series 'World' corresponds to the World's total imports from the rest of the world. The total imports for the World consist of country imports in the sample summed together, then divided by the world GDP for the same year, and multiplied by 100. World GDP sums together all countries' GDP for a particular year. 

The total import values of regional income aggregates, as a share of world GDP, have been calculated using the World Bank's income groupings. The World Bank has four income classifications: High income, Upper-middle income, Lower-middle income, and Low income. The total value of imported goods sums for High income countries, for example, sums together the import values for countries belonging to this classification, by year. This is then divided by World GDP, calculated by summing together all countries' GDP for a particular year. 

The value of global imports as a share of GDP have also been calculated for OWID continental groupings. Again, the total value of imports are summed together for each continent, for each year, which are then divided by World GDP. 

Germany's time series is comprised of West Germany, and Germany. East Germany has been excluded for the purposes of Germany's calculations.
Russia's time series comprises Russia and the USSR.
